TY  - JOUR
T1  - An Interactive Programming Method for Solving the Multiple Criteria Problem
AU  - Zionts, Stanley
AU  - Wallenius, Jyrki
Y1  - 1976/02/01
PY  - 1976
DA  - 1976/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.22.6.652
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.22.6.652
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 652
EP  - 663
VL  - 22
IS  - 6
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - In this paper a man-machine interactive mathematical programming method is presented for solving the multiple criteria problem involving a single decision maker. It is assumed that all decision-relevant criteria or objective functions are concave functions to be maximized, and that the constraint set is convex. The overall utility function is assumed to be unknown explicitly to the decision maker, but is assumed to be implicitly a linear function, and more generally a concave function of the objective functions. To solve a problem involving multiple objectives the decision maker is requested to provide answers to yes and no questions regarding certain trade offs that he likes or dislikes. Convergence of the method is proved; a numerical example is presented. Tests of the method as well as an extension of the method for solving integer linear programming problems are also described.
AB  - In this paper a man-machine interactive mathematical programming method is presented for solving the multiple criteria problem involving a single decision maker. It is assumed that all decision-relevant criteria or objective functions are concave functions to be maximized, and that the constraint set is convex. The overall utility function is assumed to be unknown explicitly to the decision maker, but is assumed to be implicitly a linear function, and more generally a concave function of the objective functions. To solve a problem involving multiple objectives the decision maker is requested to provide answers to yes and no questions regarding certain trade offs that he likes or dislikes. Convergence of the method is proved; a numerical example is presented. Tests of the method as well as an extension of the method for solving integer linear programming problems are also described.
SN  - 0025-1909
M3  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.22.6.652
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.22.6.652
Y2  - 2024/03/27
