TY  - JOUR
T1  - Production-Inventory Decisions under Order-Occurrence Risk: The Deterministic Order Quantity Case
AU  - Jesse, Richard R.
Y1  - 1976/02/01
PY  - 1976
DA  - 1976/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.22.6.664
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.22.6.664
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 664
EP  - 676
VL  - 22
IS  - 6
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper examines the problem of production-inventory decisions under order-occurrence risk. To characterize this problem briefly, let the number of periods which elapse between the receipt of orders n and n + 1 for an item be described by a probability mass function fn(s). If fn(∞) > 0, then order-occurrence risk is said to exist. That is, upon receiving order n for an item, there exists a positive probability that no future orders will occur. Assuming deterministic order quantities, the order-occurrence risk problem is formulated as a dynamic program. Optimal production-inventory disposal policies are characterized for the case of piecewise-linear production-disposal costs and concave increasing holding costs. The production cost is assumed to include a setup cost, and demand backlogging is not permitted. The production and disposal lead times are assumed to be zero.
AB  - This paper examines the problem of production-inventory decisions under order-occurrence risk. To characterize this problem briefly, let the number of periods which elapse between the receipt of orders n and n + 1 for an item be described by a probability mass function fn(s). If fn(∞) > 0, then order-occurrence risk is said to exist. That is, upon receiving order n for an item, there exists a positive probability that no future orders will occur. Assuming deterministic order quantities, the order-occurrence risk problem is formulated as a dynamic program. Optimal production-inventory disposal policies are characterized for the case of piecewise-linear production-disposal costs and concave increasing holding costs. The production cost is assumed to include a setup cost, and demand backlogging is not permitted. The production and disposal lead times are assumed to be zero.
SN  - 0025-1909
M3  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.22.6.664
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.22.6.664
Y2  - 2024/03/27
